The Hawks announced earlier this month that it has launched an official probe into state capture claims. JOHANNESBURG - Deputy President Cyril Ramaphosa says while some people have doubts about the Hawks, he is giving them the benefit of the doubt that they will get to the bottom of state capture allegations, adding that South Africans will watch the unit closely.Ramaphosa spoke at public sector union Nehawu's elective conference, which is underway in Boksburg.The Hawks announced earlier this month that it has launched an official probe into state capture claims.Cyril Ramaphosa admits there are people who don t trust the unit. Now some people may be a bit doubtful about this, and I m saying we give them the benefit of the doubt. They are the body that is responsible for investigating criminal action. He says the Hawks will be watched closely. Our people will be watching, our people will be listening, and our people will be observing everything. The deputy president, who received a warm welcome and was being referred to as incoming president, promised delegates that a commission of inquiry will be established and will be transparent and expose the truth.